Personal Statement
I’ve continued to scour for the prompt that, if no one is guiding me, the thing I want to pursue. In the summer, I decided to stay on campus. One day, I was captivated by the poster, describing functionalizing gold nanocrystals with DNA origami. I started developing my own prototypes. I researched how to functionalize proteins that viruses have high affinity to, such as sialylated glycans, to nanostructures to trap viruses. Recognizing cancerous cells have a slower rate of mutation compared to viruses, I also looked into capturing circulating tumor cells. It is here I came across the use of biomaterials, specifically scaffolds with myeloid-derived suppressor cells, to mimic pre-metastatic niche to capture extravasating metastatic cells. As I continued researching, it was like a door suddenly appeared on a wall, gradually opened, and I entered into a fantastical world. In starting to explore this world, I realized there were barriers that needed to be solved, such as instability of assembly and unintended reactivity in nanoscience and microfluidics’ interfacial effects and materials and reagents of the device affecting scaling production. I envision becoming an investigator engineering nanotechnology and biomaterials to treat pathophysiologies, as I saw that by solving composite parts, I could cumulatively improve these tools. I believe the VINSE REU will prepare me to continue developing new tools and translate these innovations so that they are accessible to patients.
	Pathways that underpinned physiological changes initiated my fascination in biology. The Stanford iGEM internship was my entryway into learning the lab techniques to characterize pathways and employ these pathways for therapeutics. The Stanford iGEM team’s project focused on competitively inhibiting DUX4-FL with a truncated isoform as a potential therapy for Facioscapulohumeral Muscular Dystrophy (FSHD). To create a better experimental model than transfecting transiently, I collaborated with the team to develop a C2C12 cell line to express mScarlet DUX4 reporter by constructing DUX4 reporter plasmids with hygromycin resistance gene and using antibiotic selection to select for cells transfected with DUX4 reporter. I also embraced a daily 3-hour commute to solidify my skills in Python. A main area I focused on was masking MRI images with the goal to segment disease-related changes indicated by hyperintensity. Ultimately, I decided to use OtsuThreshold, which calculates a threshold to separate an image into foreground and background. This internship laid my engineering foundation to transform the ideas in my mind into a tangible form. 
	Organic chemistry equipped me to consider fundamental concepts and revise wrong judgments to build the right intuition as a basis to make out of the box ideas feasible. This thinking process guided me to answer final exam questions regarding a research group’s development of a commercial synthesis for a drug to treat renal anemia. I found the paper my professor referenced, looking into their synthesis of dichlorotriazolopyridine as a key intermediate to address challenges in medicinal chemistry, namely avoiding a cryogenic reaction and column purification. From deliberations on reagent combinations forming the triazolopyridine ring, particularly their use of trifluoroacetic anhydride and MeCN for the highest yield somewhat reminiscent of the use of trifluoroacetic acid in a protection mechanism for peptide synthesis tested in the exam, I realized that details learned from materials and synthetic routes can innovate technologies. I plan to apply organic chemistry analytical considerations, such as increasing yield, interactions between target compounds, and reducing unexpected interactions to nanoscience, biomaterials, and microfluidics at VINSE REU. I’m interested in the integration between biomaterials with nanoparticles, where hydrophobicity and hydrophilicity drive the assembly of polymer nanoparticles and varying combinations of polymer blocks to balance between responding to enzymatic and oxidative degradation and protection from ROS. 
	As a research apprentice at the Fidler Lab, after assisting on various segments of the lab’s CRISPR workflow, from transplanting transfected Cas9+ hematopoietic stem cells with CRISPR knockout guides into lethally irradiated Ldlr-/- mice to conducting immunofluorescence staining, my PI invited me to investigate the role of Dmxl1 in immune cells in atherosclerosis and present a poster at a cardiovascular symposium. I hypothesized that CRISPR knockout of Dmxl1 in hematopoietic stem cells would increase the formation of atherosclerotic plaque through macrophage dysfunction because DMXL1 assists V-ATPase assembly and V-ATPase is involved in the acidification of lysosomes in macrophages. However, many of the mice in the cohort grew sick. From my literature view, I had found that global knock-out of Dmxl1 was embryonic lethal, so I inferred that knock-out of Dmxl1 in hematopoietic cells may not be a stable experimental model. From referencing Genome-Wide Associated Study, we identified another corresponding gene more related to myeloid dysfunction to continue our project to characterize genes and their pathways to drive inflammatory macrophage accumulation in atheromas. Previously assisting in the lab's experimental workflow non-sequentially, then sequentially to pursue my own questions and adapting to unexpected results, laid the foundation for planning and conducting workflows to employ biological pathways as therapeutic targets. From conducting assays to examine how cytokines and growth factors induce fibroblast-like proliferation and migration, at VINSE REU, I’m interested in modulating immune system pathways to treat diseases, while improving delivery of nanoparticles such as endosomolytic polymersomes through optimizing pH-responsiveness by considering acetal chemistry and targeting ligands. I also hope to develop therapeutics to model and investigate biological environments, such as fabricate and irradiate vasculature in microfluidic platform while responding to challenges of quantifying the temporal relationship between the increase in permeability due to radiation and recapitulating chemokine gradients to recruit neutrophils and regulating flow and shear stress. 
	At VINSE REU, I hope to continue cultivating and applying my experimental and computational skills and foundation in chemistry and biology to develop therapies and other technologies by tackling the engineering challenges to make ideas into reality. I envision assembling nanoparticles and fabricating biomaterials and microfluidic platforms to engage with a team to improve the efficacy of payload delivery, studying cellular pathways including microenvironments and their interactions, and collaborate on how the immune system affects different biological systems and can be employed in therapeutics and other approaches to help people. 

